Import CSV Data¶

  • Often one of the largest time and resource-intensive steps for data analysts

  • Requires disk space on shared network or local drives

  • Ad-hoc cleaning, more reactive to troubleshoot analytical errors

Import PGSQL Data¶

  • Centralized and organized data access locally or remotely

  • Secured and robust data storage for data persistence

  • More proactive data hygiene with integrity rules

%%timeit

engine = create_engine('postgresql+psycopg2://ctadba:cta18!@10.0.0.220/cta')

bus_month_pg = pd.read_sql("SELECT * FROM bus_month", engine)
bus_rides_pg = pd.read_sql("SELECT * FROM bus_rides", engine)

rail_stops_pg = pd.read_sql("SELECT * FROM rail_stops", engine)
rail_rides_pg = pd.read_sql("SELECT * FROM rail_rides", engine)

engine.dispose()
engine = None

Aggregate CSV Data¶

  • Data tool syntax can be formidable for newcomers or returning users

  • Complex processes require long piping/chaining of objects and methods

  • Language lacks set-based (i.e., relations, join, union) framework

Aggregate SQL Data¶

  • Clear, compact declarative language with portability

  • Processing with virtual tables occurs behind the scene

  • Set-based framework facilitates blockwise, vectorized process

In [18]:
sql = '''
      SELECT rt.route_name, COUNT(rd.rides) AS "count", 
                            SUM(rd.rides) AS "sum", 
                            AVG(rd.rides) AS "mean", 
                            MEDIAN(rd.rides) AS "median",
                            MIN(rd.rides) AS "min", 
                            MAX(rd.rides) AS "max"
      FROM bus_routes rt
      INNER JOIN bus_rides rd ON rt.route_id = rd.route_id
      GROUP BY rt.route_name
      ORDER BY SUM(rd.rides) DESC
      '''

pd.read_sql(sql, engine)

sql = '''
      SELECT rt.route_name, DATE_PART('year', rd.ride_date)::integer AS "year", 
             COUNT(rd.rides) AS "count", 
             SUM(rd.rides) AS "sum", 
             AVG(rd.rides) AS "mean", 
             MEDIAN(rd.rides) AS "median",
             MIN(rd.rides) AS "min", 
             MAX(rd.rides) AS "max"
      FROM bus_routes rt
      INNER JOIN bus_rides rd ON rt.route_id = rd.route_id
      WHERE rt.route_name IN ('79th', 'Ashland', 'Chicago', 'Western', 'Cottage Grove')
      GROUP BY rt.route_name, DATE_PART('year', rd.ride_date)::integer
      ORDER BY rt.route_name, DATE_PART('year', rd.ride_date)::integer
      '''

agg_sql = pd.read_sql(sql, engine).set_index(['route_name', 'year'])

sql = """
      SELECT Date_Part('year', rd.ride_date)::integer AS "Year",
             SUM(CASE WHEN route_name = '79th' THEN rides ELSE NULL END) AS "79th",
             SUM(CASE WHEN route_name = 'Ashland' THEN rides ELSE NULL END) AS "Ashland",
             SUM(CASE WHEN route_name = 'Chicago' THEN rides ELSE NULL END) AS "Chicago",
             SUM(CASE WHEN route_name = 'Western' THEN rides ELSE NULL END) AS "Western",
             SUM(CASE WHEN route_name = 'Cottage Grove' THEN rides ELSE NULL END) AS "Cottage Grove"
      FROM bus_routes rt
      INNER JOIN bus_rides rd ON rt.route_id = rd.route_id
      WHERE rt.route_name IN ('79th', 'Ashland', 'Chicago', 'Western', 'Cottage Grove')
      GROUP BY Date_Part('year', rd.ride_date)
      ORDER BY Date_Part('year', rd.ride_date)
      """
pvt = pd.read_sql(sql, engine).set_index('Year')

pvt.plot(kind='line', ax=ax, rot=0, marker='o')

ax.get_yaxis().set_major_formatter(FuncFormatter(lambda x, p: format(int(x), ',')))
plt.gca().set_xticks(np.unique(pvt.index.values))

plt.show()
plt.clf()
plt.close('all')

SQL Data Diagnostics¶

  • Complex processing still readable and maintainable

  • CTEs clearly show underlying tables and views without helper objects

  • Window functions allow useful inline calculations

  • Conditional aggregations clearly show reshaped data

  • Seamless casting and conversion of types with `::` operator

In [25]:
sql = """
      WITH station_agg AS
         (SELECT DATE_PART('year', r.ride_date)::integer AS "year",
                 r.station_id,
                 r.station_name,
                 COUNT(r.rides)::numeric(20,5) AS "count", 
                 SUM(r.rides)::numeric(20,5) AS "sum", 
                 AVG(r.rides)::numeric(20,5) AS "mean", 
                 MEDIAN(r.rides)::numeric(20,5) AS "median",
                 MIN(r.rides)::numeric(20,5) AS "min", 
                 MAX(r.rides)::numeric(20,5) AS "max"
          FROM rail_rides r
          GROUP BY DATE_PART('year', r.ride_date),
                   r.station_id,
                   r.station_name
          ),
                   
      merge_rail AS
         (SELECT s.*, 
                 r.rail_line,
                 (s."sum" / COUNT(*) OVER(PARTITION BY s.station_id, "year")) AS rail_total
          FROM station_agg s
          INNER JOIN rail_stations r ON s.station_id = r.station_id
         )
         
      SELECT m."year",
             SUM(rail_total) FILTER (WHERE rail_line = 'blue') AS blue,
             SUM(rail_total) FILTER (WHERE rail_line = 'brown') AS brown,
             SUM(rail_total) FILTER (WHERE rail_line = 'green') AS green,
             SUM(rail_total) FILTER (WHERE rail_line = 'orange') AS orange,
             SUM(rail_total) FILTER (WHERE rail_line = 'pink') AS pink,
             SUM(rail_total) FILTER (WHERE rail_line = 'purple') AS purple,
             SUM(rail_total) FILTER (WHERE rail_line = 'purple_exp') AS purple_exp,
             SUM(rail_total) FILTER (WHERE rail_line = 'red') AS red,
             SUM(rail_total) FILTER (WHERE rail_line = 'yellow') AS yellow
      FROM merge_rail m
      GROUP BY m."year"
      ORDER BY m."year"
      """

pvt_sql = pd.read_sql(sql, engine).set_index('year')

T-tests¶

In [46]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
from itertools import product

prod = [(i[0], i[1]) for i in product(pvt_sql.columns, pvt_sql.columns) if i[0] != i[1]]

df_dict = {}
for i in prod:
    t = ttest_ind(pvt_sql[i[0]], pvt_sql[i[1]])
